# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ebpf-security-monitoring
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] The **Berkeley Packet Filter** (**BPF**; also **BSD Packet Filter**, **classic BPF** or **cBPF**) is a network tap mechanism and packet filter which permits computer network packets to be captured and filtered at the operating system level.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] It provides a raw interface to data link layers, permitting raw link-layer packets to be sent and received, and allows a userspace process to supply a filter program that specifies which packets it wants to receive.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] For example, a tcpdump process may want to receive only packets that initiate a TCP connection.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF returns only packets that pass the filter that the process supplies.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] This avoids copying unwanted packets from the operating system kernel to the process, greatly improving performance.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] The filter program is in the form of instructions for a virtual machine, which are interpreted, or compiled into machine code by a just-in-time (JIT) mechanism and executed, in the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is used by programs that need to, among other things, analyze network traffic.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] If the driver for the network interface supports promiscuous mode, it allows the interface to be put into that mode so that all packets on the network can be received, even those destined to other hosts.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] The BPF filtering mechanism is available on most Unix-like operating systems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is sometimes used to refer to just the filtering mechanism, rather than to the entire interface.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Some systems, such as Linux and Tru64 UNIX, provide a raw interface to the data link layer other than the BPF raw interface but use the BPF filtering mechanisms for that raw interface.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] The Linux kernel provides an extended version of the BPF filtering mechanism, called eBPF, which uses a JIT mechanism, and which is used for packet filtering, as well as for other purposes in the kernel. eBPF is also available for Microsoft Windows.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] The original paper was written by Steven McCanne and Van Jacobson in 1992 while at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF provides pseudo-devices that can be bound to a network interface; reads from the device will read buffers full of packets received on the network interface, and writes to the device will inject packets on the network interface.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] While one copy remains in the receipt path for user processes, this preserves the independence of different BPF device consumers, as well as allowing the packing of headers into the BPF buffer rather than copying complete packet data.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF's filtering capabilities are implemented as an interpreter for a machine language for the BPF virtual machine, a 32-bit machine with fixed-length instructions, one accumulator, and one index register.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Programs in that language can fetch data from the packet, perform arithmetic operations on data from the packet, and compare the results against constants or against data in the packet or test bits in the results, accepting or rejecting the packet based on the results of those tests.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is often extended by "overloading" the load (ld) and store (str) instructions.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Traditional Unix-like BPF implementations can be used in userspace, despite being written for kernel-space.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] This is accomplished using preprocessor conditions.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Since version 3.18, the Linux kernel includes an extended BPF virtual machine with ten 64-bit registers, termed eBPF.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] It can be used for non-networking purposes, such as for attaching eBPF programs to various tracepoints.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Since kernel version 3.19, eBPF filters can be attached to sockets, and, since kernel version 4.1, to traffic control classifiers for the ingress and egress networking data path.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] The original and obsolete version has been retroactively renamed to *classic BPF* (*cBPF*).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Nowadays, the Linux kernel runs eBPF only and loaded cBPF bytecode is transparently translated into an eBPF representation in the kernel before program execution.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] All bytecode is verified before running to prevent denial-of-service attacks.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Until Linux 5.3, the verifier prohibited the use of loops, to prevent potentially unbounded execution times; loops with bounded execution time are now permitted in more recent kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Some projects use BPF instruction sets or execution techniques different from the originals.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Some platforms, including FreeBSD, NetBSD, and WinPcap, use a just-in-time compiler (JIT) to convert BPF instructions into native code in order to improve performance.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Linux includes a BPF JIT compiler which is disabled by default.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Kernel-mode interpreters for that same virtual machine language are used in raw data link layer mechanisms in other operating systems, such as Tru64 Unix, and for socket filters in the Linux kernel and in the WinPcap and Npcap packet capture mechanism.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] That interpreter can also be used when reading a file containing packets captured using pcap.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Another user-mode interpreter is *uBPF*, which supports JIT and eBPF (without cBPF).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Its code has been reused to provide eBPF support in non-Linux systems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Microsoft's *eBPF on Windows* builds on uBPF and the PREVAIL formal verifier.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] *rBPF*, a Rust rewrite of uBPF, is used by the Solana blockchain platform as the execution engine.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Classic BPF is generally emitted by a program from some very high-level textual rule describing the pattern to match.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] One such representation is found in libpcap.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Classic BPF and eBPF can also be written either directly as machine code, or using an assembly language for a textual representation.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Notable assemblers include Linux kernel's `bpf_asm` tool (cBPF), `bpfc` (cBPF), and the `ubpf` assembler (eBPF).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] The `bpftool` command can also act as a disassembler for both flavors of BPF.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] The assembly languages are not necessarily compatible with each other.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] eBPF bytecode has recently become a target of higher-level languages.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] LLVM added eBPF support in 2014, and GCC followed in 2019.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Both toolkits allow compiling C and other supported languages to eBPF.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] A subset of P4 can also be compiled into eBPF using BCC, an LLVM-based compiler kit.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] The Spectre attack could leverage the Linux kernel's eBPF interpreter or JIT compiler to extract data from other kernel processes.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] A JIT hardening feature in the kernel mitigates this vulnerability.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/berkeley-packet-filter] Chinese computer security group Pangu Lab said the NSA used BPF to conceal network communications as part of a complex Linux backdoor.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] It is used to safely and efficiently extend the capabilities of the kernel at runtime without requiring changes to kernel source code or loading kernel modules.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Safety is provided through an in-kernel verifier which performs static code analysis and rejects programs which crash, hang or otherwise interfere with the kernel negatively.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] This validation model differs from sandboxed environments, where the execution environment is restricted and the runtime has no insight about the program.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Examples of programs that are automatically rejected are programs without strong exit guarantees (i.e. for/while loops without exit conditions) and programs dereferencing pointers without safety checks.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Loaded programs which passed the verifier are either interpreted or in-kernel just-in-time compiled (JIT compiled) for native execution performance.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Given eBPF's efficiency and flexibility opened up new possibilities to solve production issues, Brendan Gregg famously dubbed eBPF "superpowers for Linux".
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Linus Torvalds said, "BPF has actually been really useful, and the real power of it is how it allows people to do specialized code that isn't enabled until asked for".
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Due to its success in Linux, the eBPF runtime has been ported to other operating systems such as Windows.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] eBPF evolved from the classic Berkeley Packet Filter (cBPF, a retroactively-applied name).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] At the most basic level, it introduced the use of ten 64-bit registers (instead of two 32-bit long registers for cBPF), different jump semantics, a call instruction and corresponding register passing convention, new instructions, and a different encoding for these instructions.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Map implementations are provided by the core kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] There are various types, including hash maps, arrays, and ring buffers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] The eBPF virtual machine runs within the kernel and takes in a program in the form of eBPF bytecode instructions which are converted to native machine instructions that run on the CPU.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Early implementations of eBPF saw eBPF bytecode interpreted, but this has now been replaced with a Just-in-Time (JIT) compilation process for performance and security-related reasons.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] The eBPF virtual machine consists of eleven 64-bit registers with 32-bit subregisters, a program counter and a 512-byte large BPF stack space.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] These general purpose registers keep track of state when eBPF programs are executed.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Tail calls can call and execute another eBPF program and replace the execution context, similar to how the execve() system call operates for regular processes.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] This basically allows an eBPF program to call another eBPF program.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Tail calls are implemented as a long jump, reusing the same stack frame.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Tail calls are particularly useful in eBPF, where the stack is limited to 512 bytes.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] During runtime, functionality can be added or replaced atomically, thus altering the BPF program’s execution behavior.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] A popular use case for tail calls is to spread the complexity of eBPF programs over several programs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Another use case is for replacing or extending logic by replacing the contents of the program array while it is in use.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] For example, to update a program version without downtime or to enable/disable logic.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] It is generally considered good practice in software development to group common code into a function, encapsulating logic for reusability.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Prior to Linux kernel 4.16 and LLVM 6.0, a typical eBPF C program had to explicitly direct the compiler to inline a function, resulting in a BPF object file that had duplicate functions.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] This restriction was lifted, and mainstream eBPF compilers now support writing functions naturally in eBPF programs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] This reduces the generated eBPF code size, making it friendlier to a CPU instruction cache.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] The verifier is a core component of eBPF, and its main responsibility is to ensure that an eBPF program is safe to execute.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] It performs a static analysis of the eBPF bytecode to guarantee its safety.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] The verifier analyzes the program to assess all possible execution paths.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] It steps through the instructions in order and evaluates them.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] The verification process starts with a depth-first search through all possible paths of the program, the verifier simulates the execution of each instruction using abstract interpretation, tracking the state of registers and stack if any instruction could lead to an unsafe state, verification fails.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] This process continues until all paths have been analyzed or a violation is found.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Depending on the type of program, the verifier checks for violations of specific rules.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] This is not an exhaustive list of the checks the verifier does, and there are exceptions to these rules.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] An example is that tracing programs have access to helpers that allow them to read memory in a controlled way, but these program types require root privileges and thus do not pose a security risk.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Over time the eBPF verifier has evolved to include newer features and optimizations, such as support for bounded loops, dead-code elimination, function-by-function verification, and callbacks.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] eBPF programs use the memory and data structures from the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Some structures can be modified between different kernel versions, altering the memory layout.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Since the Linux kernel is continuously developed, there is no guarantee that the internal data structures will remain the same across different versions.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] CO-RE is a fundamental concept in modern eBPF development that allows eBPF programs to be portable across different kernel versions and configurations.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] It addresses the challenge of kernel structure variations between different Linux distributions and versions.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] CO-RE comprises BTF (BPF Type Format) - a metadata format that describes the types used in the kernel and eBPF programs and provides detailed information about struct layouts, field offsets, and data types.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] It enables runtime accessibility of kernel types, which is crucial for BPF program development and verification.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] BTF is included in the kernel image of BTF-enabled kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Special relocations are emitted by the compiler (e.g., LLVM).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] These relocations capture high-level descriptions of what information the eBPF program intends to access.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] The libbpf library adapts eBPF programs to work with the data structure layout on the target kernel where they run, even if this layout is different from the kernel where the code was compiled.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] To do this, libbpf needs the BPF CO-RE relocation information generated by Clang as part of the compilation process.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] The compiled eBPF program is stored in an Executable and Linkable Format (ELF) object file.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] This file contains BTF-type information and Clang-generated relocations.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] The ELF format allows the eBPF loader (e.g., libbpf) to process and adjust the BPF program dynamically for the target kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] At the first eBPF Summit there was a vote taken and the bee mascot was named "eBee".
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] The logo was originally created by Vadim Shchekoldin.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Earlier unofficial eBPF mascots have existed in the past, but have not seen widespread adoption.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] The eBPF Foundation was created in August 2021 with the goal to expand the contributions being made to extend the powerful capabilities of eBPF and grow beyond Linux.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Founding members include Meta, Google, Isovalent, Microsoft and Netflix.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] The purpose is to raise, budget, and spend funds in support of various open source, open data and/or open standards projects relating to eBPF technologies to further drive the growth and adoption of the eBPF ecosystem.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Since inception, Red Hat, Huawei, Crowdstrike, Tigera, DaoCloud, Datoms, FutureWei also joined.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Due to the ease of programmability, eBPF has been used as a tool for implementing microarchitectural timing side-channel attacks such as Spectre against vulnerable microprocessors.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] While unprivileged eBPF implements mitigations against Spectre v1, v2, and v4 for x86-64, unprivileged use has ultimately been disabled by the kernel community by default to protect users of unsupported architectures and limit the impact of future hardware vulnerabilities.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] On x86-64, Spectre v1 is mitigated through a combination of branchless bounds-enforcement (e.g., masking instructions) and the verification of speculative execution paths.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/ebpf] Spectre v4 is mitigated exclusively through speculation barriers (i.e., lfence) and Spectre v2 is mitigated through retpoline when available or speculation barriers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A **kernel** is a computer program at the core of a computer's operating system that always has complete control over everything in the system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is also responsible for preventing and mitigating conflicts between different processes.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] It is the portion of the operating system that is always resident in memory and facilitates interactions between hardware and software components.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A full kernel controls all hardware resources (e.g.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] I/O, memory, cryptography) via device drivers, arbitrates conflicts between processes concerning such resources, and optimizes the use of common resources, such as CPU, cache, file systems, and network sockets.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] On most systems, the kernel is one of the first programs loaded on startup (after the bootloader).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] It handles the rest of startup as well as memory, peripherals, and input/output (I/O) requests from software, translating them into data-processing instructions for the central processing unit.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The critical code of the kernel is usually loaded into a separate area of memory, which is protected from access by application software or other less critical parts of the operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel performs its tasks, such as scheduling processes, managing hardware devices such as the hard disk, and handling interrupts, in this protected kernel space.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In contrast, application programs such as browsers, word processors, or audio or video players use a separate area of memory, user space.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This prevents user data and kernel data from interfering with each other and causing instability and slowness, as well as preventing malfunctioning applications from affecting other applications or crashing the entire operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Even in systems where the kernel is included in application address spaces, memory protection is used to prevent unauthorized applications from modifying the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel's interface is a low-level abstraction layer.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a process requests a service from the kernel, it must invoke a system call, usually through a wrapper function.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] There are different kernel architecture designs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels run entirely in a single address space with the CPU executing in supervisor mode, mainly for speed.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels run most but not all of their services in user space, like user processes do, mainly for resilience and modularity.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] MINIX 3 is a notable example of microkernel design.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some kernels, such as the Linux kernel, are both monolithic and modular, since they can insert and remove loadable kernel modules at runtime.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This central component of a computer system is responsible for executing programs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel takes responsibility for deciding at any time which of the many running programs should be allocated to the processor or processors.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Random-access memory (RAM) is used to store both program instructions and data.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Typically, both need to be present in memory for a program to execute.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often, multiple programs will want memory access, frequently demanding more memory than the computer has available.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is responsible for deciding which memory each process can use, and determining what to do when insufficient memory is available.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] I/O devices include, but are not limited to, peripherals such as keyboards, mice, disk drives, printers, USB devices, network adapters, and display devices.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel provides convenient methods for applications to use these devices, which are typically abstracted by the kernel so that applications do not need to know their implementation details.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Key aspects necessary in resource management are defining the execution domain (address space) and the protection mechanism used to mediate access to the resources within a domain.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Kernels also provide methods for synchronization and inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] These implementations may be located within the kernel itself or the kernel can also rely on other processes it is running.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Although the kernel must provide IPC in order to provide access to the facilities provided by each other, kernels must also provide running programs with a method to make requests to access these facilities.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is also responsible for context switching between processes or threads.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel has full access to the system's memory and must allow processes to safely access this memory as they require it.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often the first step in doing this is virtual addressing, usually achieved by paging and/or segmentation.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual addressing allows the kernel to make a given physical address appear to be another address, the virtual address.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual address spaces may be different for different processes; the memory that one process accesses at a particular (virtual) address may be different memory from what another process accesses at the same address.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This allows every program to behave as if it is the only one (apart from the kernel) running and thus prevents applications from crashing each other.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] On many systems, a program's virtual address may refer to data that is not currently in memory.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The layer of indirection provided by virtual addressing allows the operating system to use other data stores, like a hard drive, to store what would otherwise have to remain in main memory (RAM).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] As a result, operating systems can allow programs to use more memory than the system has physically available.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a program needs data that is not currently in RAM, the CPU signals to the kernel that this has happened, and the kernel responds by writing the contents of an inactive memory block to disk (if necessary) and replacing it with the data requested by the program.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The program can then be resumed from the point where it was stopped.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This scheme is generally known as demand paging.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual addressing also allows creation of virtual partitions of memory in two disjoint areas, one being reserved for the kernel (kernel space) and the other for the applications (user space).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The applications are not permitted by the processor to address kernel memory, thus preventing an application from damaging the running kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This fundamental partition of memory space has contributed much to the current designs of actual general-purpose kernels and is almost universal in such systems, although some research kernels (e.g., Singularity) take other approaches.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] To perform useful functions, processes need access to the peripherals connected to the computer, which are controlled by the kernel through device drivers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A device driver is a computer program encapsulating, monitoring and controlling a hardware device (via its hardware/software interface (HSI)) on behalf of the OS.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] It provides the operating system with an API, procedures and information about how to control and communicate with a certain piece of hardware.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Device drivers are an important and vital dependency for all OS and their applications.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The design goal of a driver is abstraction; the function of the driver is to translate the OS-mandated abstract function calls (programming calls) into device-specific calls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In theory, a device should work correctly with a suitable driver.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Device drivers are used for e.g. host adapters, video cards, sound cards, printers, scanners, modems, and network interface controllers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] For example, to show the user something on the screen, an application would make a request to the kernel, which would forward the request to its display driver, which is then responsible for actually plotting the character/pixel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A kernel must maintain a list of available devices.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In plug-and-play systems, a device manager first performs a scan on different peripheral buses, such as Peripheral Component Interconnect (PCI) or Universal Serial Bus (USB), to detect installed devices, then searches for the appropriate drivers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] As device management is a very OS-specific topic, these drivers are handled differently by each kind of kernel design, but in every case, the kernel has to provide the I/O to allow drivers to physically access their devices through some port or memory location.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Important decisions have to be made when designing the device management system, as in some designs accesses may involve context switches, making the operation very CPU-intensive and easily causing a significant performance overhead.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In computing, a system call is how a process requests a service from an operating system's kernel that it does not normally have permission to run.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] System calls provide the interface between a process and the operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most operations interacting with the system require permissions not available to a user-level process, e.g., I/O performed with a device present on the system, or any form of communication with other processes requires the use of system calls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A system call is a mechanism that is used by the application program to request a service from the operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] They use a machine-code instruction that causes the processor to change mode.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] An example would be from supervisor mode to protected mode.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is where the operating system performs actions like accessing hardware devices or the memory management unit.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Generally the operating system provides a library that sits between the operating system and normal user programs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Usually it is a C library such as Glibc or Windows API.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The library handles the low-level details of passing information to the kernel and switching to supervisor mode.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] System calls include close, open, read, wait and write.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] To actually perform useful work, a process must be able to access the services provided by the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is implemented differently by each kernel, but most provide a C library or an API, which in turn invokes the related kernel functions.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The method of invoking the kernel function varies from kernel to kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] If memory isolation is in use, it is impossible for a user process to call the kernel directly, because that would be a violation of the processor's access control rules.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] An important consideration in the design of a kernel is the support it provides for protection from faults (fault tolerance) and from malicious behaviours (security).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] These two aspects are usually not clearly distinguished, and the adoption of this distinction in the kernel design leads to the rejection of a hierarchical structure for protection.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Support for hierarchical protection domains is typically implemented using CPU modes.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many kernels implement "capabilities", i.e., objects provided to user code that allow limited access to an underlying object managed by the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A common example is file handling: a file is a representation of information stored on a permanent storage device.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel may be able to perform many different operations, including read, write, delete or execute, but a user-level application may only be permitted to perform some of these operations (e.g., it may only be allowed to read the file).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A common implementation of this is for the kernel to provide an object to the application (typically called a "file handle") that the application may then invoke operations on, the validity of which the kernel checks at the time the operation is requested.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Such a system may be extended to cover all objects that the kernel manages, and indeed to objects provided by other user applications.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] An efficient and simple way to provide hardware support of capabilities is to delegate to the memory management unit (MMU) the responsibility of checking access-rights for every memory access, a mechanism called capability-based addressing.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most commercial computer architectures lack such MMU support for capabilities; the Capability Hardware Enhanced RISC Instructions (CHERI) project is developing capability-based mechanisms for several architectures.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] An alternative approach is to simulate capabilities using commonly supported hierarchical domains.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In this approach, each protected object must reside in an address space that the application does not have access to; the kernel also maintains a list of capabilities in such memory.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The performance cost of address space switching limits the practicality of this approach in systems with complex interactions between objects, but it is used in current operating systems for objects that are not accessed frequently or that are not expected to perform quickly.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] If the firmware does not support protection mechanisms, it is possible to simulate protection at a higher level, for example by simulating capabilities by manipulating page tables, but there are performance implications.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Lack of hardware support may not be an issue, however, for systems that choose to use language-based protection.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] An important kernel design decision is the choice of the abstraction levels where the security mechanisms and policies should be implemented.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Kernel security mechanisms play a critical role in supporting security at higher levels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] One approach is to use firmware and kernel support for fault tolerance (see above), and build the security policy for malicious behavior on top of that (adding features such as cryptography mechanisms where necessary), delegating some responsibility to the compiler.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Approaches that delegate enforcement of security policy to the compiler and/or the application level are often called *language-based security*.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The lack of many critical security mechanisms in current mainstream operating systems impedes the implementation of adequate security policies at the application abstraction level.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, a common misconception in computer security is that any security policy can be implemented in an application regardless of kernel support.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] According to Mars Research Group developers, a lack of isolation is one of the main factors undermining kernel security.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] They propose their driver isolation framework for protection, primarily in the Linux kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Typical computer systems today use hardware-enforced rules about what programs are allowed to access what data.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The processor monitors the execution and stops a program that violates a rule, such as a user process that tries to write to kernel memory.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In systems that lack support for capabilities, processes are isolated from each other by using separate address spaces.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Calls from user processes into the kernel are regulated by requiring them to use one of the above-described system call methods.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] An alternative approach is to use language-based protection.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In a language-based protection system, the kernel will only allow code to execute that has been produced by a trusted language compiler.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The language may then be designed such that it is impossible for the programmer to instruct it to do something that will violate a security requirement.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Examples of systems with language-based protection include JX and Microsoft's Singularity.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Edsger Dijkstra proved that from a logical point of view, atomic lock and unlock operations operating on binary semaphores are sufficient primitives to express any functionality of process cooperation.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Nonetheless, this approach is generally held to be lacking in terms of safety and efficiency, whereas a message passing approach is more flexible.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A number of other approaches (either lower- or higher-level) are available as well, with many modern kernels providing support for systems such as shared memory and remote procedure calls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The idea of a kernel where I/O devices are handled uniformly with other processes, as parallel co-operating processes, was first proposed and implemented by Brinch Hansen (although similar ideas were suggested in 1967).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In Hansen's description of this, the "common" processes are called *internal processes*, while the I/O devices are called *external processes*.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Similar to physical memory, allowing applications direct access to controller ports and registers can cause the controller to malfunction, or system to crash.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] With this, depending on the complexity of the device, some devices can get surprisingly complex to program, and use several different controllers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Because of this, providing a more abstract interface to manage the device is important.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This interface is normally done by a device driver or hardware abstraction layer.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Frequently, applications will require access to these devices.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel must maintain the list of these devices by querying the system for them in some way.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This can be done through the BIOS, or through one of the various system buses (such as PCI/PCIE, or USB).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Using an example of a video driver, when an application requests an operation on a device, such as displaying a character, the kernel needs to send this request to the current active video driver.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The video driver, in turn, needs to carry out this request.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is an example of inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The above listed tasks and features can be provided in many ways that differ from each other in design and implementation.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The principle of *separation of mechanism and policy* is the substantial difference between the two main philosophies of microkernels and monolithic kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Here a *mechanism* is the support that allows the implementation of many different policies, while a *policy* is a particular "mode of operation".
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Because the mechanism and policy are separated, the policy can be easily changed to, e.g., require the use of a security token.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel instead tends to include many policies, therefore restricting the rest of the system to rely on them.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Computer scientist Per Brinch Hansen argued in favour of separation of mechanism and policy.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The failure to properly fulfill this separation is one of the major causes of the lack of substantial innovation in existing operating systems, a problem common in computer architecture.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic design is induced by the "kernel mode"/"user mode" architectural approach to protection (technically called hierarchical protection domains), which is common in conventional commercial systems; in fact, every module needing protection is therefore preferably included into the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] While monolithic kernels execute all of their code in the same address space (kernel space), microkernels try to run most of their services in user space, aiming to improve maintainability and modularity of their codebase.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most kernels do not fit exactly into one of these categories, but are rather found in between these two designs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] More exotic designs such as nanokernels and exokernels are available, but are seldom used for production systems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The Xen hypervisor, for example, is an exokernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In a monolithic kernel, all OS services are part of the kernel and run in kernel mode, thus also residing in the same memory area.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This approach provides rich and powerful hardware access.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] UNIX developer Ken Thompson stated that "it is in [his] opinion easier to implement a monolithic kernel".
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The main disadvantages of monolithic kernels are the dependencies between system components – a bug in a device driver might crash the entire system, for example – and the fact that large kernels can become very difficult to maintain.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Thompson also stated that "It is also easier for [a monolithic kernel] to turn into a mess in a hurry as it is modified".
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels, which have traditionally been used by Unix-like operating systems, contain all the operating system core functions and the device drivers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel is one single program that contains all of the code necessary to perform every kernel-related task.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Every part that is to be accessed by a program that cannot be put in a library is in the kernel space, including drivers, schedulers, memory management, file systems, and network stacks.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many system calls are provided to applications, to allow them to access all those services.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel, while initially loaded with subsystems that may not be needed, can be tuned to a point where it is as fast as or faster than one that was specifically designed for the hardware, although more relevant in a general sense.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most work in the monolithic kernel is done via system calls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] These are interfaces, usually kept in a tabular structure, that access some subsystem within the kernel, such as disk operations.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Essentially, calls are made within programs and a checked copy of the request is passed through the system call.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic Linux kernel can be made extremely small not only because of its ability to dynamically load modules but also because of its ease of customization.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, there are some versions that are small enough to fit together with a large number of utilities and other programs on a single floppy disk and still provide a fully functional operating system (one of the most popular of which is muLinux).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This ability to miniaturize its kernel has also led to a rapid growth in the use of Linux in embedded systems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels consist of the core functions of the operating system and the device drivers with the ability to load modules at runtime.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] They provide rich and powerful abstractions of the underlying hardware.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] They provide a small set of simple hardware abstractions and use applications called servers to provide more functionality.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This particular approach defines a high-level virtual interface over the hardware, with a set of system calls to implement operating system services such as process management, concurrency and memory management in several modules that run in supervisor mode.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A microkernel that is designed for a specific platform or device is only ever going to have what it needs to operate.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The microkernel approach consists of defining a simple abstraction over the hardware, with a set of primitives or system calls to implement minimal OS services such as memory management, multitasking, and inter-process communication.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other services, including those normally provided by the kernel, such as networking, are implemented in user-space programs, referred to as *servers*.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels are easier to maintain than monolithic kernels, but the large number of system calls and context switches might slow down the system because they typically generate more overhead than plain function calls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Only parts that really require being in a privileged mode are in kernel space, such as IPC (Inter-Process Communication), a basic scheduler or scheduling primitives, basic memory handling, and basic I/O primitives.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many critical parts are now running in user space, including the complete scheduler, memory handling, file systems, and network stacks.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels were invented as a reaction to traditional "monolithic" kernel design, whereby all system functionality was put in one static program running in a special "system" mode of the processor.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In the microkernel, only the most fundamental of tasks are performed at this level, such as being able to access some (not necessarily all) of the hardware, manage memory and coordinate message passing between the processes.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some systems that use microkernels are QNX and GNU Hurd.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In the case of QNX and GNU Hurd, user sessions can be entire snapshots of the system itself, or "views" as it is referred to.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most microkernels use a message passing system to handle requests from one server to another.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The message passing system generally operates on a port basis with the microkernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] As an example, if a request for more memory is sent, a port is opened with the microkernel and the request sent through.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Once within the microkernel, the steps are similar to system calls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The rationale was that it would bring modularity in the system architecture, which would entail a cleaner system that is easier to debug or dynamically modify, customizable to users' needs, and higher performing.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels are part of operating systems like GNU Hurd, MINIX, MkLinux, QNX and Redox OS.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Although microkernels are very small by themselves, in combination with all their required auxiliary code they are, in fact, often larger than monolithic kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Advocates of monolithic kernels also point out that the two-tiered structure of microkernel systems, in which most of the operating system does not interact directly with the hardware, creates a not-insignificant cost in terms of system efficiency.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels normally provide only the minimal services such as defining memory address spaces, inter-process communication (IPC) and process management.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other functions, such as running hardware processes, are not handled directly by microkernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Proponents of microkernels point out those monolithic kernels have the disadvantage that an error in the kernel can cause the entire system to crash.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] With a microkernel, however, if a kernel process crashes, it is still possible to prevent a crash of the system as a whole by merely restarting the service that caused the error.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other services provided by the kernel such as networking are implemented in user-space programs referred to as *servers*.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Servers allow the operating system to be modified by simply starting and stopping programs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] For a machine without networking support, for instance, the networking server is not started.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The task of moving in and out of the kernel to move data between the various applications and servers creates overhead that is detrimental to the efficiency of microkernels in comparison with monolithic kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Disadvantages in the microkernel exist, however.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The disadvantages for microkernels are extremely context-based.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] As an example, they work well for small single-purpose (and critical) systems because if not many processes need to run, then the complications of process management are effectively mitigated.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A microkernel allows the implementation of the remaining part of the operating system as programs running in user mode, and the use of different operating systems on top of the same unchanged kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] It is also possible to dynamically switch among operating systems and to have more than one active simultaneously.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] As the computer kernel grows, so grows the size and vulnerability of its trusted computing base, in addition to its memory footprint.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is mitigated to some degree by perfecting a virtual memory system, but not all computer architectures have virtual memory support.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] To reduce the kernel's footprint, extensive editing has to be performed to carefully remove unneeded code, which can be very difficult with non-obvious interdependencies between parts of a kernel with millions of lines of code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] By the early 1990s, due to the various shortcomings of monolithic kernels versus microkernels, monolithic kernels were considered obsolete by virtually all operating system researchers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] As a result, the design of Linux as a monolithic kernel rather than a microkernel was the topic of a famous debate between Linus Torvalds and Andrew Tanenbaum.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] There is merit on both sides of the argument presented in the Tanenbaum–Torvalds debate.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels are designed to have all of their code in the same address space (kernel space), which some developers argue is necessary to increase the performance of the system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some developers also maintain that monolithic systems are extremely efficient if well written.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic model tends to be more efficient through the use of shared kernel memory, rather than the slower IPC system of microkernel designs, which is typically based on message passing.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The performance of microkernels was poor in both the 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Studies that empirically measured the performance of these microkernels did not analyze the reasons of such inefficiency.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The explanations of this data were left to "folklore", with the assumption that they were due to the increased frequency of switches from "kernel-mode" to "user-mode", to the increased frequency of inter-process communication and to the increased frequency of context switches.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, as guessed in 1995, the reasons for the poor performance of microkernels might as well have been: (1) an actual inefficiency of the whole microkernel *approach*, (2) the particular *concepts* implemented in those microkernels, and (3) the particular *implementation* of those concepts.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Therefore it remained to be studied if the solution to build an efficient microkernel was, unlike previous attempts, to apply the correct construction techniques.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Hybrid kernels are used in some commercial operating systems, including most versions of Microsoft Windows to date (NT 3.1, NT 3.5, NT 3.51, NT 4.0, 2000, XP, Vista, 7, 8, 8.1, 10 and 11).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Apple's macOS uses a hybrid kernel called XNU, which is based upon code from OSF/1's Mach kernel (OSFMK 7.3) and FreeBSD's monolithic kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Hybrid kernels are similar to microkernels, except they include some additional code in kernel-space to increase performance.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] These kernels represent a compromise that was implemented by some developers to accommodate the major advantages of both monolithic and microkernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels are extensions of microkernels with some properties of monolithic kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Unlike monolithic kernels, these types of kernels are unable to load modules at runtime on their own.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This implies running some services (such as the network stack or the filesystem) in kernel space to reduce the performance overhead of a traditional microkernel, but still running kernel code (such as device drivers) as servers in user space.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many traditionally monolithic kernels support loadable kernel modules.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The most well known of these kernels is the Linux kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The modular kernel essentially can have parts of it that are built into the core kernel binary or binaries that load into memory on demand.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A code-tainted module has the potential to destabilize a running kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] By contrast, it is possible to write a driver for a microkernel in a completely separate memory space and test it before "going" live.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a kernel module is loaded, it accesses the monolithic portion's memory space by adding to it what it needs, therefore opening the doorway to possible pollution.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Modules, generally, communicate with the kernel using a module interface of some sort.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] The interface is generalized (although particular to a given operating system) so it is not always possible to use modules.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often the device drivers may need more flexibility than the module interface affords.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Essentially, it is two system calls and often the safety checks that only have to be done once in the monolithic kernel now may be done twice.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A nanokernel delegates virtually all services – including even the most basic ones like interrupt controllers or the timer – to device drivers to make the kernel memory requirement even smaller than a traditional microkernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Exokernels are a still-experimental approach to operating system design.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] They differ from other types of kernels in limiting their functionality to the protection of and multiplexing of access to the raw hardware, providing no hardware abstractions on top of which to develop applications.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] This separation of hardware protection from hardware management enables application developers to determine how to make the most efficient use of the available hardware for each specific program.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Exokernels in themselves are extremely small.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Nonetheless, they are accompanied by library operating systems (see also unikernel), providing application developers with the functionalities of a conventional operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A major advantage of exokernel-based systems is that they can incorporate multiple library operating systems, each exporting a different API, for example one for high level UI development and one for real-time control.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] A multikernel operating system treats a multi-core machine as a network of independent cores, as if it were a distributed system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] It does not assume shared memory but rather implements inter-process communications as message passing.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p01] Barrelfish was the first operating system to be described as a multikernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Strictly speaking, an operating system (and thus, a kernel) is not *required* to run a computer.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Programs can be directly loaded and executed on the "bare metal" machine, provided that the authors of those programs are willing to work without any hardware abstraction or operating system support.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Most early computers operated this way during the 1950s and early 1960s, which were reset and reloaded between the execution of different programs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Eventually, small ancillary programs such as program loaders and debuggers were left in memory between runs, or loaded from ROM.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] As these were developed, they formed the basis of what became early operating system kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] The "bare metal" approach is still used today on some video game consoles and embedded systems, but in general, newer computers use modern operating systems and kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] In 1969, the RC 4000 Multiprogramming System introduced the system design philosophy of a small nucleus "upon which operating systems for different purposes could be built in an orderly manner", what would be called the microkernel approach.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the decade preceding Unix, computers had grown enormously in power – to the point where computer operators were looking for new ways to get people to use their spare time on their machines.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] One of the major developments during this era was time-sharing, whereby a number of users would get small slices of computer time, at a rate at which it appeared they were each connected to their own, slower, machine.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] The development of time-sharing systems led to a number of problems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] One was that users, particularly at universities where the systems were being developed, wanted to hack the system to get more CPU time.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] For this reason, security and access control became a major focus of the Multics project in 1965.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Another ongoing issue was properly handling computing resources: users spent most of their time staring at the terminal and thinking about what to input instead of actually using the resources of the computer, and a time-sharing system should give the CPU time to an active user during these periods.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Finally, the systems typically offered a memory hierarchy several layers deep, and partitioning this expensive resource led to major developments in virtual memory systems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] The Commodore Amiga was released in 1985, and was among the first – and certainly most successful – home computers to feature an advanced kernel architecture.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] The AmigaOS kernel's executive component, *exec.library*, uses a microkernel message-passing design, but there are other kernel components, like *graphics.library*, that have direct access to the hardware.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] There is no memory protection, and the kernel is almost always running in user mode.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Only special actions are executed in kernel mode, and user-mode applications can ask the operating system to execute their code in kernel mode.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] During the design phase of Unix, programmers decided to model every high-level device as a file, because they believed the purpose of computation was data transformation.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] For instance, printers were represented as a "file" at a known location – when data was copied to the file, it printed out.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Other systems, to provide a similar functionality, tended to virtualize devices at a lower level – that is, both devices *and* files would be instances of some lower level concept.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Virtualizing the system at the file level allowed users to manipulate the entire system using their existing file management utilities and concepts, dramatically simplifying operation.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] As an extension of the same paradigm, Unix allows programmers to manipulate files using a series of small programs, using the concept of pipes, which allowed users to complete operations in stages, feeding a file through a chain of single-purpose tools.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although the end result was the same, using smaller programs in this way dramatically increased flexibility as well as ease of development and use, allowing the user to modify their workflow by adding or removing a program from the chain.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the Unix model, the *operating system* consists of two parts: first, the huge collection of utility programs that drive most operations; second, the kernel that runs the programs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Over the years the computing model changed, and Unix's treatment of everything as a file or byte stream no longer was as universally applicable as it was before.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although a terminal could be treated as a file or a byte stream, which is printed to or read from, the same did not seem to be true for a graphical user interface.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Even if network communication can be compared to file access, the low-level packet-oriented architecture dealt with discrete chunks of data and not with whole files.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] As the capability of computers grew, Unix became increasingly cluttered with code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] It is also because the modularity of the Unix kernel is extensively scalable.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] While kernels might have had 100,000 lines of code in the seventies and eighties, kernels like Linux, of modern Unix successors like GNU, have more than 13 million lines.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Modern Unix-derivatives are generally based on module-loading monolithic kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Examples of this are the Linux kernel in the many distributions of GNU, IBM AIX, as well as the Berkeley Software Distribution variant kernels such as FreeBSD, DragonFly BSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD, and macOS.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apart from these alternatives, amateur developers maintain an active operating system development community, populated by self-written hobby kernels that mostly end up sharing many features with Linux, FreeBSD, DragonflyBSD, OpenBSD, or NetBSD kernels and/or being compatible with them.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apple first launched its classic Mac OS in 1984, bundled with its Macintosh personal computer.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apple moved to a nanokernel design in Mac OS 8.6.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Against this, the modern macOS (originally named Mac OS X) is based on Darwin, which uses a hybrid kernel called XNU, which was created by combining the 4.3BSD kernel and the Mach kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Microsoft Windows was first released in 1985 as an add-on to MS-DOS.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Because of its dependence on another operating system, initial releases of Windows, prior to Windows 95, were considered an operating environment (not to be confused with an operating system).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] This product line continued to evolve through the 1980s and 1990s, with the Windows 9x series adding 32-bit addressing and pre-emptive multitasking; but ended with the release of Windows Me in 2000.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Microsoft also developed Windows NT, an operating system with a very similar interface, but intended for high-end and business users.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] This line started with the release of Windows NT 3.1 in 1993, and was introduced to general users with the release of Windows XP in October 2001—replacing Windows 9x with a completely different, much more sophisticated operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] This is the line that continues with Windows 11.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] The architecture of Windows NT's kernel is considered a hybrid kernel because the kernel itself contains tasks such as the Window Manager and the IPC Managers, with a client/server layered subsystem model.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] It was designed as a modified microkernel, as the Windows NT kernel was influenced by the Mach microkernel but does not meet all of the criteria of a pure microkernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Supervisory program or supervisor is a computer program, usually part of an operating system, that controls the execution of other routines and regulates work scheduling, input/output operations, error actions, and similar functions and regulates the flow of work in a data processing system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Historically, this term was essentially associated with IBM's line of mainframe operating systems starting with OS/360.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] In other operating systems, the supervisor is generally called the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the 1970s, IBM further abstracted the supervisor state from the hardware, resulting in a hypervisor that enabled full virtualization, i.e. the capacity to run multiple operating systems on the same machine totally independent of each other.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Hence the first such system was called *Virtual Machine* or *VM*.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although Mach, developed by Richard Rashid at Carnegie Mellon University, is the best-known general-purpose microkernel, other microkernels have been developed with more specific aims.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] The L4 microkernel family (mainly the L3 and the L4 kernel) was created to demonstrate that microkernels are not necessarily slow.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Newer implementations such as Fiasco and Pistachio are able to run Linux next to other L4 processes in separate address spaces.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/kernel-operating-system-p02] Additionally, QNX is a microkernel that is principally used in embedded systems, and the open-source software MINIX, while originally created for educational purposes, is now focused on being a highly reliable and self-healing microkernel OS.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The **Linux kernel** is a free and open-source Unix-like kernel that is used in many computer systems worldwide.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel was created by Linus Torvalds in 1991 and was soon adopted as the kernel for the GNU operating system (OS), which was created to be a free replacement for Unix.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Since the late 1990s, it has been included in many operating system distributions, many of which are called Linux.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] One such Linux kernel operating system is Android, which is used in many mobile and embedded devices.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Most of the kernel code is written in C as supported by the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), which has extensions beyond standard C.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The code also contains assembly code for architecture-specific logic such as optimizing memory use and task execution.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel has a modular design such that modules can be integrated as software components – including dynamically loaded.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel is monolithic in an architectural sense since the entire OS kernel runs in kernel space.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is provided under the GNU General Public License version 2, although it contains files under other compatible licenses.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In 1991, Linus Torvalds was a computer science student enrolled at the University of Helsinki.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] During his time there, he began to develop an operating system as a side-project inspired by UNIX, for a personal computer.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] He started with a task switcher in Intel 80386 assembly language and a terminal driver.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] On 17 September 1991, Torvalds prepared version 0.01 of Linux and put on the "ftp.funet.fi" – FTP server of the Finnish University and Research Network (FUNET).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] It was not even executable since its code still needed Minix to compile and test it.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] On 5 October 1991, Torvalds announced the first "official" version of Linux, version 0.02.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] At the time, the GNU Project had completed many components for its free UNIX replacement, GNU, but its kernel, the GNU Hurd, was incomplete.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The project adopted the Linux kernel for its OS.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Torvalds labeled the kernel with major version 0 to indicate that it was not yet intended for general use.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Version 0.11, released in December 1991, was the first version to be self-hosted; compiled on a computer running the Linux kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] When Torvalds released version 0.12 in January 1992, he adopted the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2) over his previous self-drafted license, which had not permitted commercial redistribution.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In contrast to Unix, all Linux source files are freely available, including device drivers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The initial success of Linux was driven by programmers and testers across the world.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Because Linux implemented Unix-like system call semantics and exposed the standard POSIX APIs through an implementation of the C standard library, Linux could run software and applications that had been originally developed for Unix.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] On 19 January 1992, the first post to the new newsgroup *alt.os.linux* was submitted.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] On 31 March 1992, the newsgroup was renamed *comp.os.linux*.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The fact that Linux is a monolithic kernel rather than a microkernel was the topic of a debate between Andrew S.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Tanenbaum, the creator of MINIX, and Torvalds.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The Tanenbaum–Torvalds debate started in 1992 on the Usenet group *comp.os.minix* as a general discussion about kernel architectures.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Version 0.96 released in May 1992 was the first capable of running the X Window System.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In March 1994, Linux 1.0.0 was released with 176,250 lines of code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] As indicated by the version number, it was the first version considered suitable for a production environment.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In June 1996, after release 1.3, Torvalds decided that Linux had evolved enough to warrant a new major number, and so labeled the next release as version 2.0.0.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Significant features of 2.0 included symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), support for more processors types and support for selecting specific hardware targets and for enabling architecture-specific features and optimizations.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The *make *config* family of commands of *kbuild* enable and configure options for building ad hoc kernel executables (vmlinux) and loadable modules.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.2, released on 20 January 1999, improved locking granularity and SMP management, added m68k, PowerPC, Sparc64, Alpha, and other 64-bit platforms support.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Furthermore, it added new file systems including Microsoft's NTFS read-only capability.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In 1999, IBM published its patches to the Linux 2.2.13 code for the support of the S/390 architecture.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.4.0, released on 4 January 2001, contained support for ISA Plug and Play, USB, and PC Cards.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Linux 2.4 added support for the Pentium 4 and Itanium (the latter introduced the ia64 ISA that was jointly developed by Intel and Hewlett-Packard to supersede the older PA-RISC), and for the newer 64-bit MIPS processor.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Development for 2.4.*x* changed a bit in that more features were made available throughout the series, including support for Bluetooth, Logical Volume Manager (LVM) version 1, RAID support, InterMezzo and ext3 file systems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Version 2.6.0 was released on 17 December 2003.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The development for 2.6.*x* changed further towards including new features throughout the series.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Starting with 2.6.x releases, the kernel supported a large number of file systems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Some were designed for Linux, like ext3, ext4, FUSE, and Btrfs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Others were native to other operating systems like JFS, XFS, Minix, Xenix, Irix, Solaris, System V, Windows, and MS-DOS.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Though development had not used a version control system thus far, in 2002, Linux developers adopted BitKeeper, which was made freely available to them even though it was not free software.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In 2005, because of efforts to reverse-engineer it, the company that owned the software revoked its support of the Linux community.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In response, Torvalds and others wrote Git.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The new system was written within weeks, and in two months the first official kernel made using it was released.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In 2005 the *stable team* was formed as a response to the lack of a kernel tree where people could work on bug fixes, and it would keep updating *stable* versions.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In February 2008 the *linux-next* tree was created to serve as a place where patches aimed to be merged during the next development cycle gathered.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Several subsystem maintainers also adopted the suffix *-next* for trees containing code that they mean to submit for inclusion in the next release cycle.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] As of January 2014, the in-development version of Linux is held in an unstable branch named *linux-next*.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The 20th anniversary of Linux was celebrated by Torvalds in July 2011 with the release of version 3.0.0.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] As 2.6 had been the version number for 8 years, a new *uname26* personality that reports 3.x as 2.6.40+x had to be added to the kernel so that old programs would work.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Version 3.0 was released on 22 July 2011.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] On 30 May 2011, Torvalds announced that the big change was "NOTHING.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Absolutely nothing." and asked, "...let's make sure we really make the next release not just an all new shiny number, but a good kernel too." After the expected 6–7 weeks of the development process, it would be released near the 20th anniversary of Linux.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The same series unified support for the ARM processor.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The numbering change from 2.6.39 to 3.0, and from 3.19 to 4.0, involved no meaningful technical differentiation; the major version number was increased simply to avoid large minor numbers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Stable 3.x.y kernels were released until 3.19 in February 2015.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Version 3.11, released on 2 September 2013, added many new features such as the new O_TMPFILE flag for `open(2)` to reduce temporary file vulnerabilities, experimental AMD Radeon dynamic power management, low-latency network polling, and zswap (compressed swap cache).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In April 2015, Torvalds released kernel version 4.0.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] By February 2015, Linux had received contributions from nearly 12,000 programmers from more than 1,200 companies, including some of the world's largest software and hardware vendors.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Version 4.1 of Linux, released in June 2015, contains over 19.5 million lines of code contributed by almost 14,000 programmers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] A total of 1,991 developers, of whom 334 were first-time collaborators, added more than 553,000 lines of code to version 5.8, breaking the record previously held by version 4.9.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] According to the Stack Overflow's annual Developer Survey of 2019, more than 53% of all respondents have developed software for Linux and about 27% for Android, although only about 25% develop with Linux-based operating systems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Most websites run on Linux-based operating systems, and all of the world's 500 most powerful supercomputers run on Linux.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Linux distributions bundle the kernel with system software (e.g., the GNU C Library, systemd, and other Unix utilities and daemons) and a wide selection of application software, but their usage share in desktops is low in comparison to other operating systems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Android, which runs on a modified Linux kernel, accounts for the majority of mobile device operating systems, and is increasingly being used in embedded devices, making it a significant driver of Linux adoption.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The cost to redevelop version 2.6.0 of the Linux kernel in a traditional proprietary development setting has been estimated to be US$612 million (€467M, £394M) in 2004 prices using the COCOMO person-month estimation model.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In 2006, a study funded by the European Union put the redevelopment cost of kernel version 2.6.8 higher, at €882M ($1.14bn, £744M).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] This topic was revisited in October 2008 by Amanda McPherson, Brian Proffitt, and Ron Hale-Evans.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Wheeler's methodology, they estimated redevelopment of the 2.6.25 kernel now costs $1.3bn (part of a total $10.8bn to redevelop Fedora 9).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Again, Garcia-Garcia and Alonso de Magdaleno from University of Oviedo (Spain) estimate that the value annually added to kernel was about €100M between 2005 and 2007 and €225M in 2008, it would cost also more than €1bn (about $1.4bn as of February 2010) to develop in the European Union.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] As of 7 March 2011, using then-current LOC (lines of code) of a 2.6.x Linux kernel and wage numbers with David A.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Wheeler's calculations it would cost approximately $3bn (about €2.2bn) to redevelop the Linux kernel as it keeps getting bigger.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] An updated calculation as of 26 September 2018, using then-current 20,088,609 LOC (lines of code) for the 4.14.14 Linux kernel and the current US national average programmer salary of $75,506 show that it would cost approximately $14,725,449,000 (£11,191,341,000) to rewrite the existing code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Most who use Linux do so via a Linux distribution.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Some distributions ship the vanilla or stable kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Several vendors (such as Red Hat and Debian) maintain a customized source tree.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Graph of the sizes of Linux Kernel versions in millions of lines of code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The community of Linux kernel developers comprises about 5000–6000 members.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] According to the "2017 State of Linux Kernel Development", a study issued by the Linux Foundation, covering the commits for the releases 4.8 to 4.13, about 1500 developers were contributing from about 200–250 companies on average.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The top 30 developers contributed a little more than 16% of the code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] For companies, the top contributors are Intel (13.1%) and Red Hat (7.2%), Linaro (5.6%), IBM (4.1%), the second and fifth places are held by the 'none' (8.2%) and 'unknown' (4.1%) categories.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Prominent Linux kernel developers have been aware of the importance of avoiding conflicts between developers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] For a long time there was no code of conduct for kernel developers due to opposition by Torvalds.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] A Linux Kernel *Code of Conflict* was introduced on 8 March 2015.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] It was replaced on 16 September 2018 by a new *Code of Conduct* based on the Contributor Covenant.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] This coincided with a public apology by Torvalds and a brief break from kernel development.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] On 30 November 2018, complying with the *Code of Conduct*, Jarkko Sakkinen of Intel sent out patches replacing instances of "fuck" appearing in source code comments with suitable versions focused on the word 'hug'.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Developers who feel treated unfairly can report this to the Linux Foundation Technical Advisory Board.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In July 2013, the maintainer of the USB 3.0 driver Sage Sharp asked Torvalds to address the abusive commentary in the kernel development community.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In 2014, Sharp backed out of Linux kernel development, saying that "The focus on technical excellence, in combination with overloaded maintainers, and people with different cultural and social norms, means that Linux kernel maintainers are often blunt, rude, or brutal to get their job done".
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] At the linux.conf.au (LCA) conference in 2018, developers expressed the view that the culture of the community has gotten much better in the past few years.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Daniel Vetter, the maintainer of the Intel drm/i915 graphics kernel driver, commented that the "rather violent language and discussion" in the kernel community has decreased or disappeared.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Laurent Pinchart asked developers for feedback on their experiences with the kernel community at the 2017 Embedded Linux Conference Europe.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The issues brought up were discussed a few days later at the Maintainers Summit.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Concerns over the lack of consistency in how maintainers responded to patches submitted by developers were echoed by Shuah Khan, the maintainer of the kernel self-test framework.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Torvalds contended that there would never be consistency in the handling of patches because different kernel subsystems have, over time, adopted different development processes.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Therefore, it was agreed upon that each kernel subsystem maintainer would document the rules for patch acceptance.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel source code, a.k.a. source tree, is managed in the Git version control system – also created by Torvalds.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] As of 2021, the 5.11 release of the Linux kernel had around 30.34 million lines of code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Roughly 14% of the code is part of the "core," including architecture-specific code, kernel code, and memory management code, while 60% is drivers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Contributions are submitted as patches, in the form of text messages on the Linux kernel mailing list (LKML) (and often also on other mailing lists dedicated to particular subsystems).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The patches must conform to a set of rules and to a formal language that, among other things, describes which lines of code are to be deleted and what others are to be added to the specified files.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] These patches can be automatically processed so that system administrators can apply them in order to make just some changes to the code or to incrementally upgrade to the next version.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is distributed also in GNU zip (gzip) and bzip2 formats.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] A developer who wants to change the Linux kernel writes and tests a code change.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Depending on how significant the change is and how many subsystems it modifies, the change will either be submitted as a single patch or in multiple patches of source code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In case of a single subsystem that is maintained by a single maintainer, these patches are sent as e-mails to the maintainer of the subsystem with the appropriate mailing list in Cc.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The maintainer and the readers of the mailing list will review the patches and provide feedback.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Once the review process has finished the subsystem maintainer accepts the patches in the relevant Git kernel tree.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] If the changes to the Linux kernel are bug fixes that are considered important enough, a pull request for the patches will be sent to Torvalds within a few days.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Otherwise, a pull request will be sent to Torvalds during the next merge window.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The merge window usually lasts two weeks and starts immediately after the release of the previous kernel version.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The Git kernel source tree names all developers who have contributed to the Linux kernel in the *Credits* directory and all subsystem maintainers are listed in *Maintainers*.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] As with many large open-source software projects, developers are required to adhere to the Contributor Covenant, a code of conduct intended to address harassment of minority contributors.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Additionally, to prevent offense the use of inclusive terminology within the source code is mandated.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Linux is written in a special C programming language supported by GCC, a compiler that extends the C standard in many ways, for example using inline sections of code written in the assembly language (in GCC's "AT&T-style" syntax) of the target architecture.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Initial support for the Rust programming language was added in Linux 6.1, which was released in December 2022, with later kernel versions, such as Linux 6.2 and Linux 6.3, further improving the support.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] As for most software, the kernel is versioned as a series of dot-separated numbers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] For early versions, the version consisted of three or four dot-separated numbers called *major release*, *minor release* and *revision.* At that time, odd-numbered minor releases were for development and testing, while even numbered minor releases for production.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The optional fourth digit indicated a patch level.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Development releases were indicated with a release candidate suffix (*-rc*).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The current versioning conventions are different.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The odd/even number implying dev/prod has been dropped, and a major version is indicated by the first two numbers together.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] While the time-frame is open for the development of the next major, the -rcN suffix is used to identify the n'th release candidate for the next version.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] For example, the release of the version 4.16 was preceded by seven 4.16-rcN (from -rc1 to -rc7).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Once a stable version is released, its maintenance is passed to the *stable team*.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Updates to a stable release are identified by a three-number scheme (e.g., 4.16.1, 4.16.2, ...).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel is usually built with the GNU toolchain.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The GNU C compiler, GNU cc, part of the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), is the default compiler for mainline Linux.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The GNU Assembler (often called GAS or GNU as) outputs the object files from the GCC generated assembly code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Finally, the GNU Linker (GNU ld) produces a statically linked executable kernel file called vmlinux.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Both as and ld are part of GNU Binary Utilities (binutils).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] GNU cc was for a long time the only compiler capable of correctly building Linux.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In 2004, Intel claimed to have modified the kernel so that its C compiler was also capable of compiling it.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] There was another such reported success in 2009, with a modified 2.6.22 version.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Support for the Intel compiler has been dropped in 2023.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Since 2010, effort has been underway to build Linux with Clang, an alternative compiler for the C language; as of 12 April 2014, the official kernel could almost be compiled by Clang.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The project dedicated to this effort is named *LLVMLinux* after the LLVM compiler infrastructure upon which Clang is built.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] LLVMLinux does not aim to fork either Linux or the LLVM, therefore it is a meta-project composed of patches that are eventually submitted to the upstream projects.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] By enabling Linux to be compiled by Clang, developers may benefit from shorter compilation times.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In 2017, developers completed upstreaming patches to support building the Linux kernel with Clang in the 4.15 release, having backported support for X86-64 and AArch64 to the 4.4, 4.9, and 4.14 branches of the stable kernel tree.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Google's Pixel 2 shipped with the first Clang built Linux kernel, though patches for Pixel (1st generation) did exist.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] 2018 saw ChromeOS move to building kernels with Clang by default, while Android made Clang and LLVM's linker LLD required for kernel builds in 2019.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Google moved its production kernel used throughout its datacenters to being built with Clang in 2020.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The *ClangBuiltLinux* group coordinates fixes to both Linux and LLVM to ensure compatibility, both composed of members from *LLVMLinux* and having upstreamed patches from *LLVMLinux*.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] As with any software, problems with the Linux kernel can be difficult to troubleshoot.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Common challenges relate to userspace vs. kernel space access, misuse of synchronization primitives, and incorrect hardware management.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] An oops is a non-fatal error in the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] After such an error, operations continue with suspect reliability.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] A panic (generated by panic()) is a fatal error.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] After such an error, the kernel prints a message and halts the computer.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The kernel provides for *debugging by printing* via printk(), which stores messages in a circular buffer (overwriting older entries with newer).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The syslog(2) system call provides for reading and clearing the message buffer and for setting the maximum *log level* of the messages to be sent to the console.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Kernel messages are also exported to userland through the */dev/kmsg* interface.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The *ftrace* mechanism allow for debugging by tracing.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] It is used for monitoring and debugging Linux at runtime and it can analyze user space latencies due to kernel misbehavior.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Furthermore, *ftrace* allows users to trace Linux at boot-time.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] With KGDB Linux can be debugged in much the same way as userspace programs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] KGDB requires an additional machine that runs GDB and that is connected to the target to be debugged using a serial cable or Ethernet.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The Linux kernel project integrates new code on a rolling basis.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Standard operating procedure is that software checked into the project must work and compile without error.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Each kernel subsystem is assigned a maintainer who is responsible for reviewing patches against the kernel code standards and keeping a queue of patches that can be submitted to Torvalds within a merge window that is usually several weeks.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Patches are merged by Torvalds into the source code of the prior stable Linux kernel release, creating the release candidate (-rc) for the next stable release.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Once the merge window is closed, only fixes to the new code in the development release are accepted.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The -rc development release of the kernel goes through regression testing and once it is considered stable by Torvalds and the subsystem maintainers, a new version is released and the development process starts over again.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The Git tree that contains the Linux kernel source code is referred to as **mainline Linux**.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Every stable kernel release originates from the mainline tree, and is frequently published on kernel.org.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Mainline Linux has only solid support for a small subset of the many devices that run Linux.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Non-mainline support is provided by independent projects, such as Yocto or Linaro, but in many cases the kernel from the device vendor is needed.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Using a vendor kernel likely requires a board support package.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Maintaining a kernel tree outside of mainline Linux has proven to be difficult.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The maintainer of the stable branch, Greg Kroah-Hartman, has applied the term *Linux-like* to downstream kernel forks by vendors that add millions of lines of code to the mainline kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In 2019, Google stated that it wanted to use the mainline Linux kernel in Android so the number of kernel forks would be reduced.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The term Linux-like has also been applied to the Embeddable Linux Kernel Subset, which does not include the full mainline Linux kernel but a small modified subset of the code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] There are certain communities that develop kernels based on the official Linux.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Some interesting bits of code from these forks that include Linux-libre, Compute Node Linux, INK, L4Linux, RTLinux, and User-Mode Linux (UML) have been merged into the mainline.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Some operating systems developed for mobile phones initially used heavily modified versions of Linux, including Google Android, Firefox OS, HP webOS, Nokia Maemo and Jolla Sailfish OS.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Today Android uses a customized Linux where major changes are implemented in device drivers, but some changes to the core kernel code is required.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Android developers also submit patches to the official Linux that finally can boot the Android operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] For example, a Nexus 7 can boot and run the mainline Linux.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The latest version and older versions are maintained separately.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Most of the latest kernel releases were supervised by Torvalds.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The Linux kernel developer community maintains a stable kernel by applying fixes for software bugs that have been discovered during the development of the subsequent stable kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Therefore, www.kernel.org always lists two stable kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] The next stable Linux kernel is released about 8 to 12 weeks later.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Some releases are designated for long-term support as *longterm* with bug fix releases for two or more years.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] Some projects have attempted to reduce the size of the Linux kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p01] In 2014, Josh Triplett started the -tiny source tree for a reduced size version.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Even though seemingly contradictory, the Linux kernel is both monolithic and modular.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel is classified as a monolithic kernel architecturally since the entire OS runs in kernel space.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The design is modular since it can be assembled from modules that in some cases are loaded and unloaded at runtime.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] It supports features once only available in closed source kernels of non-free operating systems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The rest of the article makes use of the UNIX and Unix-like operating systems convention of the manual pages.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The number that follows the name of a command, interface, or other feature specifies the section (i.e. the type of the OS' component or feature) it belongs to.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] For example execve(2) refers to a system call, and exec(3) refers to a userspace library wrapper.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The following is an overview of architectural design and of noteworthy features.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Most device drivers and kernel extensions run in kernel space (ring 0 in many CPU architectures), with full access to the hardware.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Some exceptions run in user space; notable examples are filesystems based on FUSE/CUSE, and parts of UIO.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Furthermore, the X Window System and Wayland, the windowing system and display server protocols that most people use with Linux, do not run within the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Differently, the actual interfacing with GPUs of graphics cards is an in-kernel subsystem called Direct Rendering Manager (DRM).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Unlike standard monolithic kernels, device drivers are easily configured as modules, and loaded or unloaded while the system is running and can also be pre-empted under certain conditions in order to handle hardware interrupts correctly and to better support symmetric multiprocessing.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] By choice, Linux has no stable device driver application binary interface.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux typically makes use of memory protection and virtual memory and can also handle non-uniform memory access, the project has absorbed μClinux, which also makes it possible to run Linux on microcontrollers without virtual memory.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The hardware is represented in the file hierarchy.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] User applications interact with device drivers via entries in the /dev or /sys directories.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Process information is mapped into the /proc directory.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux started as a clone of UNIX, and aims toward POSIX and Single UNIX Specification compliance.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel provides system calls and other interfaces that are Linux-specific.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] In order to be included in the official kernel, the code must comply with a set of licensing rules.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux application binary interface (ABI) between the kernel and the user space has four degrees of stability (stable, testing, obsolete, removed); The system calls are expected to never change in order to preserve compatibility for userspace programs that rely on them.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Loadable kernel modules (LKMs), by design, cannot rely on a stable ABI.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Therefore, they must always be recompiled whenever a new kernel executable is installed in a system, otherwise they will not be loaded.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] In-tree drivers that are configured to become an integral part of the kernel executable (vmlinux) are statically linked by the build process.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] There is no guarantee of stability of source-level in-kernel API and, because of this, device driver code, as well as the code of any other kernel subsystem, must be kept updated with kernel evolution.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Any developer who makes an API change is required to fix any code that breaks as the result of their change.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The set of the Linux kernel API that regards the interfaces exposed to user applications is fundamentally composed of UNIX and Linux-specific system calls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] A system call is an entry point into the Linux kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] For example, among the Linux-specific ones there is the family of the clone(2) system calls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Most extensions must be enabled by defining the `_GNU_SOURCE` macro in a header file or when the user-land code is being compiled.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] System calls can only be invoked via assembly instructions that enable the transition from unprivileged user space to privileged kernel space in ring 0.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] For this reason, the C standard library (libC) acts as a wrapper to most Linux system calls, by exposing C functions that, if needed, transparently enter the kernel, which will execute on behalf of the calling process.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] For system calls not exposed by libC, such as the fast userspace mutex, the library provides a function called syscall(2), which can be used to explicitly invoke them.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Pseudo filesystems (e.g., the sysfs and procfs filesystems) and special files (e.g., `/dev/random`, `/dev/sda`, `/dev/tty`, and many others) constitute another layer of interface to kernel data structures representing hardware or logical (software) devices.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] This issue is mainly due to distribution-specific configurations and a set of patches applied to the code of the Linux kernel, differences in system libraries, services (daemons), filesystem hierarchies, and environment variables.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The main standard concerning application and binary compatibility of Linux distributions is the Linux Standard Base (LSB).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The LSB goes beyond what concerns the Linux kernel, because it also defines the desktop specifications, the X libraries and Qt that have little to do with it.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The LSB version 5 is built upon several standards and drafts (POSIX, SUS, X/Open, File System Hierarchy (FHS), and others).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The standard ABI for how x86_64 user programs invoke system calls is to load the syscall number into the *rax* register, and the other parameters into *rdi*, *rsi*, *rdx*, *r10*, *r8*, and *r9*, and finally to put the *syscall* assembly instruction in the code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] There are several internal kernel APIs between kernel subsystems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux developers chose not to maintain a stable in-kernel ABI.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Modules compiled for a specific version of the kernel cannot be loaded into another version without being recompiled.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux, as other kernels, has the ability to manage processes including creating, suspending, resuming and terminating.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Unlike other operating systems, the Linux kernel implements processes as a group of threads called tasks.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] If two tasks share the same TGID, then they are called in the kernel terminology a task group.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Each task is represented by a *task_struct* data structure.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] A new process can be created by calling clone family of system calls or fork system call.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Processes can be suspended and resumed by the kernel by sending signals like SIGSTOP and SIGCONT.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] A process can terminate itself by calling exit system call, or terminated by another process by sending signals like SIGKILL, SIGABRT or SIGINT.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] If the executable is dynamically linked to shared libraries, a dynamic linker is used to find and load the needed objects, prepare the program to run and then run it.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The Native POSIX Thread Library (NPTL) provides the POSIX standard thread interface (*pthreads*) to userspace.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel isn't aware of processes nor threads but it is aware of *tasks*, thus threads are implemented in userspace.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Threads in Linux are implemented as *tasks* sharing resources, while if they aren't sharing called to be independent processes.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel provides the futex(7) (fast user-space mutex) mechanisms for user-space locking and synchronization.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The majority of the operations are performed in userspace but it may be necessary to communicate with the kernel using the futex(2) system call.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] As opposed to userspace threads described above, *kernel threads* run in kernel space.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] They are threads created by the kernel itself for specialized tasks; they are privileged like the kernel and aren't bound to any process or application.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux process scheduler is modular, in the sense that it enables different scheduling classes and policies.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Scheduler classes are pluggable scheduler algorithms that can be registered with the base scheduler code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Each class schedules different types of processes.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The core code of the scheduler iterates over each class in order of priority and chooses the highest priority scheduler that has a schedulable entity of type struct sched_entity ready to run.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Entities may be threads, group of threads, and even all the processes of a specific user.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux provides both user preemption as well as (selectable, up to) full kernel preemption.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Preemption reduces latency, increases responsiveness, and makes Linux more suitable for desktop and real-time applications.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] This comes at a cost of throughput, as work being interrupted worsens cache behavior.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] For normal tasks, by default, the kernel uses the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) class, introduced in version 2.6.23.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The scheduler is defined as a macro in a C header as `SCHED_NORMAL`.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] In other POSIX kernels, a similar policy known as `SCHED_OTHER` allocates CPU timeslices (i.e, it assigns absolute slices of the processor time depending on either predetermined or dynamically computed priority of each process).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] With user preemption, the kernel scheduler can replace the current process with the execution of a context switch to a different one that therefore acquires the computing resources for running (CPU, memory, and more).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] With kernel preemption, the kernel can preempt itself when an interrupt handler returns, when kernel tasks block, and whenever a subsystem explicitly calls the schedule() function.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel also contains two POSIX-compliant real-time scheduling classes named `SCHED_FIFO` (realtime first-in-first-out) and `SCHED_RR` (realtime round-robin), both of which take precedence over the default class.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] An additional scheduling policy known as `SCHED_DEADLINE`, implementing the earliest deadline first algorithm (EDF), was added in kernel version 3.14, released on 30 March 2014.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] `SCHED_DEADLINE` takes precedence over all the other scheduling classes.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) scheduler, to prevent the need for CFS "latency nice" patches.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The EEVDF scheduler replaced CFS in version 6.6 of the Linux kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel has different causes of concurrency (e.g., interrupts, bottom halves, preemption of kernel and users tasks, symmetrical multiprocessing).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] They consist of atomic types (which can only be manipulated by a set of specific operators), spinlocks, semaphores, mutexes, and lockless algorithms (e.g., RCUs).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Most lock-less algorithms are built on top of memory barriers for the purpose of enforcing memory ordering and prevent undesired side effects due to compiler optimization.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] PREEMPT_RT code included in mainline Linux provide *RT-mutexes*, a special kind of Mutex that do not disable preemption and have support for priority inheritance.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Almost all locks are changed into sleeping locks when using configuration for realtime operation.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Priority inheritance avoids priority inversion by granting a low-priority task that holds a contended lock the priority of a higher-priority waiter until that lock is released.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux includes a kernel lock validator called *Lockdep*.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Although the management of interrupts could be seen as a single job, it is divided into two.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] This split in two is due to the different time constraints and to the synchronization needs of the tasks whose the management is composed of.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The first part is made up of an asynchronous interrupt service routine (ISR) that in Linux is known as the *top half*, while the second part is carried out by one of three types of the so-called *bottom halves* (*softirq*, *tasklets,* and *work queues*).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux interrupt service routines can be nested.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] A new IRQ can trap into a high priority ISR that preempts any other lower priority ISR.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux kernel manages both physical and virtual memory.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] It divides physical memory into zones, each of which has a specific purpose.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Those zones are the most common, but others exist.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux implements virtual memory with 4 or 5-level page tables.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel is not pageable (meaning it is always resident in physical memory and cannot be swapped to the disk) and there is no memory protection (no SIGSEGV signals, unlike in user space), therefore memory violations lead to instability and system crashes.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] User memory is pageable by default, although paging for specific memory areas can be disabled with the `mlock()` system call family.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Page frame information is maintained in apposite data structures (of type `struct page`) that are populated immediately after boot and kept until shutdown, regardless of whether they are associated with virtual pages.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The physical address space is divided into different zones, according to architectural constraints and intended use.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] NUMA systems with multiple memory banks are also supported.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Small chunks of memory can be dynamically allocated in kernel space via the family of `kmalloc()` APIs and freed with the appropriate variant of `kfree()`.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] `vmalloc()` and `kvfree()` are used for large virtually contiguous chunks.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] `alloc_pages()` allocates the desired number of entire pages.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The kernel used to include the SLAB, SLUB and SLOB allocators as configurable alternatives.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The SLOB allocator was removed in Linux 6.4 and the SLAB allocator was removed in Linux 6.8.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The sole remaining allocator is SLUB, which aims for simplicity and efficiency, is PREEMPT_RT compatible and was introduced in Linux 2.6.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Since Linux supports numerous filesystems with different features and functionality, it is necessary to implement a generic filesystem that is independent from underlying filesystems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The virtual file system interfaces with other Linux subsystems, userspace, or APIs and abstracts away the different implementations of underlying filesystems.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] VFS implements system calls like `create`, `open`, `read`, `write` and `close`.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] VFS implements a generic superblock and inode block that is independent from the one that the underlying filesystem has.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] In this subsystem directories and files are represented by a `struct file` data structure.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] When userspace requests access to a file it is returned a file descriptor (non negative integer value) but in kernel space it is a `struct file` structure.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] This structure stores all the information the kernel knows about a file or directory.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] sysfs and procfs are virtual filesystems that expose hardware information and userspace programs' runtime information.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] These filesystems aren't present on disk and instead the kernel implements them as a callback or routine that gets called when they are accessed by userspace.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] While not originally designed to be portable, Linux is now one of the most widely ported operating system kernels, running on a diverse range of systems from the ARM architecture to IBM z/Architecture mainframe computers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The first port was performed on the Motorola 68000 platform.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The modifications to the kernel were so fundamental that Torvalds viewed the Motorola version as a fork and a "Linux-like operating system".
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] That moved Torvalds to lead a major restructure of the code to facilitate porting to more computing architectures.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The first Linux that, in a single source tree, had code for more than i386 alone, supported the DEC Alpha AXP 64-bit platform.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux is used as the primary operating system on IBM’s Summit supercomputer.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] In October 2019, all systems on the TOP500 list of the world’s fastest supercomputers ran operating systems based on the Linux kernel, whereas the first Linux-based supercomputer appeared on the list in 1998.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux has also been ported to various handheld devices such as iPhone 3G and iPod.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] In 2007, the LKDDb project has been started to build a comprehensive database of hardware and protocols known by Linux kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The database is built automatically by static analysis of the kernel sources.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Later in 2014, the Linux Hardware project was launched to automatically collect a database of all tested hardware configurations with the help of users of various Linux distributions.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Kernel updates can be applied without rebooting by using live patching technologies such as Ksplice, kpatch and kGraft.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Initial support for live kernel patching was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in version 4.0, released on 12 April 2015.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The feature, known as *livepatch*, uses the kernel's ftrace functionality and provides a common infrastructure for hot patches supplied through kernel modules, together with interfaces for userspace management tools.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] In its initial Linux 4.0 implementation, livepatch support was limited to the x86 architecture and provided basic infrastructure rather than a complete live-patching consistency model.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Kernel bugs present potential security issues.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] For example, they may allow for privilege escalation or create denial-of-service attack vectors.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Over the years, numerous bugs affecting system security were found and fixed.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] New features are frequently implemented to improve the kernel's security.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Capabilities(7) have already been introduced in the section about the processes and threads.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Android makes use of them and systemd gives administrators detailed control over the capabilities of processes.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux offers a wealth of mechanisms to reduce kernel attack surface and improve security that are collectively known as the Linux Security Modules (LSM).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] They comprise the Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) module, whose code has been originally developed and then released to the public by the NSA, and AppArmor among others.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] SELinux is now actively developed and maintained on GitHub.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] SELinux and AppArmor provide support to access control security policies, including mandatory access control (MAC), though they profoundly differ in complexity and scope.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Another security feature is the Seccomp BPF (SECure COMPuting with Berkeley Packet Filters), which works by filtering parameters and reducing the set of system calls available to user-land applications.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux distributions typically release security updates to fix vulnerabilities in the Linux kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Many offer long-term support releases that receive security updates for a certain Linux kernel version for an extended period of time.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] In 2024, researchers disclosed that the Linux kernel contained a serious vulnerability, CVE-2024-50264, located in the AF_VSOCK subsystem.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] This bug is a use-after-free flaw, a class of memory corruption issue that occurs when a program continues to use memory after it has been freed.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Such flaws are particularly dangerous in the kernel, as they can allow attackers to escalate privileges.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Initially, Torvalds released Linux under a license that forbade any commercial use.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] This was changed in version 0.12 by a switch to the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] This license allows distribution and sale of possibly modified and unmodified versions of Linux but requires that all those copies be released under the same license and be accompanied by - or that, on request, free access is given to - the complete corresponding source code.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds has described licensing Linux under the GPLv2 as the "best thing I ever did".
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The Linux kernel is licensed explicitly under GNU General Public License version 2 only (GPL-2.0-only) with an explicit syscall exception (Linux-syscall-note), without offering the licensee the option to choose any later version, which is a common GPL extension.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Contributed code must be available under GPL-compatible license.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] There was considerable debate about how easily the license could be changed to use later GPL versions (including version 3), and whether this change is even desirable.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds himself specifically indicated upon the release of version 2.4.0 that his own code is released only under version 2.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The terms of the GPL state that if no version is specified, then any version may be used, and Alan Cox pointed out that very few other Linux contributors had specified a particular version of the GPL.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] In September 2006, a survey of 29 key kernel programmers indicated that 28 preferred GPLv2 to the then-current GPLv3 draft.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] They referred to clauses regarding DRM/tivoization, patents, "additional restrictions" and warned a Balkanisation of the "Open Source Universe" by the GPLv3.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds, who decided not to adopt the GPLv3 for the Linux kernel, reiterated his criticism even years later.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] It is debated whether some loadable kernel modules (LKMs) are to be considered derivative works under copyright law, and thereby whether or not they fall under the terms of the GPL.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] In accordance with the license rules, LKMs using only a public subset of the kernel interfaces are non-derived works, thus Linux gives system administrators the mechanisms to load out-of-tree binary objects into the kernel address space.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] There are some out-of-tree loadable modules that make legitimate use of the *dma_buf* kernel feature.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] GPL compliant code can certainly use it.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] A different possible use case would be Nvidia Optimus that pairs a fast GPU with an Intel integrated GPU, where the Nvidia GPU writes into the Intel framebuffer when it is active.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] But, Nvidia cannot use this infrastructure because it necessitates bypassing a rule that can only be used by LKMs that are also GPL.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Alan Cox replied on LKML, rejecting a request from one of Nvidia's engineers to remove this technical enforcement from the API.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Torvalds clearly stated on the LKML that "[I] claim that binary-only kernel modules ARE derivative "by default"'".
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] On the other hand, Torvalds has also said that "[one] gray area in particular is something like a driver that was originally written for another operating system (i.e., clearly not a derived work of Linux in origin).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] THAT is a gray area, and _that_ is the area where I personally believe that some modules may be considered to not be derived works simply because they weren't designed for Linux and don't depend on any special Linux behaviour".
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Proprietary graphics drivers, in particular, are heavily discussed.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Whenever proprietary modules are loaded into Linux, the kernel marks itself as being "tainted", and therefore bug reports from tainted kernels will often be ignored by developers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] The official kernel, that is, Torvalds's git branch at the kernel.org repository, contains binary blobs released under the terms of the GNU GPLv2 license.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux can also load binary blobs, proprietary firmware, drivers, or other executable modules from the filesystem, and link them into kernel space.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linux is a registered trademark of Linus Torvalds in the United States, the European Union, and some other countries.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] A legal battle over the trademark began in 1996, when William Della Croce, a lawyer who was never involved in the development of Linux, started requesting licensing fees for the use of the word *Linux*.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] After it was proven that the word was in common use long before Della Croce's claimed first use, the trademark was awarded to Torvalds.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] In October 2024, during the Russian invasion of Ukraine, kernel developer Greg Kroah-Hartman removed some kernel developers whose email addresses suggested a connection to Russia from their roles as maintainers.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] Linus Torvalds responded that he did not support Russian aggression and would not revert the patch, insinuating that opponents of the patch were Russian trolls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/linux-kernel-p02] James Bottomley, a kernel developer, issued an apology for the handling of the situation and clarified that the action was a consequence of U.S. sanctions against Russia.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/seccomp] seccomp mode is enabled via the `prctl(2)` system call using the `PR_SET_SECCOMP` argument, or (since Linux kernel 3.17) via the `seccomp(2)` system call. seccomp mode used to be enabled by writing to a file, `/proc/self/seccomp`, but this method was removed in favor of `prctl()`.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/seccomp] In some kernel versions, seccomp disables the `RDTSC` x86 instruction, which returns the number of elapsed processor cycles since power-on, used for high-precision timing.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/seccomp] Some consider seccomp comparable to OpenBSD pledge(2) and FreeBSD capsicum(4).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/seccomp] seccomp was first devised by Andrea Arcangeli in January 2005 for use in public grid computing and was originally intended as a means of safely running untrusted compute-bound programs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/seccomp] It was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in kernel version 2.6.12, which was released on March 8, 2005.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] In computing, a **system call** (**syscall**) is the programmatic way in which a computer program requests a service from the operating system on which it is executed.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] This may include hardware-related services (for example, accessing a hard disk drive or accessing the device's camera), creation and execution of new processes, and communication with integral kernel services such as process scheduling.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] System calls provide an essential interface between a process and the operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] In most systems, system calls can only be made from userspace processes, while in some systems, OS/360 and successors for example, privileged system code also issues system calls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] For embedded systems, system calls typically do not change the privilege mode of the CPU.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] The architecture of most modern processors, with the exception of some embedded systems, involves a security model.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] However, many applications need access to these components, so system calls are made available by the operating system to provide well-defined, safe implementations for such operations.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] The operating system executes at the highest level of privilege, and allows applications to request services via system calls, which are often initiated via interrupts.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] An interrupt automatically puts the CPU into some elevated privilege level and then passes control to the kernel, which determines whether the calling program should be granted the requested service.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] If the service is granted, the kernel executes a specific set of instructions over which the calling program has no direct control, returns the privilege level to that of the calling program, and then returns control to the calling program.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] Generally, systems provide a library or API that sits between normal programs and the operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] On Unix-like systems, that API is usually part of an implementation of the C library (libc), such as glibc, that provides wrapper functions for the system calls, often named the same as the system calls they invoke.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] On Windows NT, that API is part of the Native API, in the ntdll.dll library; this is an undocumented API used by implementations of the regular Windows API and directly used by some system programs on Windows.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] The library's wrapper functions expose an ordinary function calling convention (a subroutine call on the assembly level) for using the system call, as well as making the system call more modular.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] Here, the primary function of the wrapper is to place all the arguments to be passed to the system call in the appropriate processor registers (and maybe on the call stack as well), and also setting a unique system call number for the kernel to call.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] In this way the library, which exists between the OS and the application, increases portability.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] The call to the library function itself does not cause a switch to kernel mode and is usually a normal subroutine call (using, for example, a "CALL" assembly instruction in some Instruction set architectures (ISAs)).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] The actual system call does transfer control to the kernel (and is more implementation-dependent and platform-dependent than the library call abstracting it).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] For example, in Unix-like systems, `fork` and `execve` are C library functions that in turn execute instructions that invoke the `fork` and `exec` system calls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] On exokernel based systems, the library is especially important as an intermediary.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] On exokernels, libraries shield user applications from the very low level kernel API, and provide abstractions and resource management.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] IBM's OS/360, DOS/360 and TSS/360 implement most system calls through a library of assembly language macros, although there are a few services with a call linkage.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] This reflects their origin at a time when programming in assembly language was more common than high-level language usage.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] IBM system calls were therefore not directly executable by high-level language programs, but required a callable assembly language wrapper subroutine.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] Since then, IBM has added many services that can be called from high level languages in, e.g., z/OS and z/VSE.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] In more recent release of MVS/SP and in all later MVS versions, some system call macros generate Program Call (PC).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] On Unix, Unix-like and other POSIX-compliant operating systems, popular system calls are `open`, `read`, `write`, `close`, `wait`, `exec`, `fork`, `exit`, and `kill`.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] Many modern operating systems have hundreds of system calls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] For example, Linux and OpenBSD each have over 300 different calls, NetBSD has close to 500, FreeBSD has over 500, Windows has close to 2000, divided between win32k (graphical) and ntdll (core) system calls while Plan 9 has 54.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] Tools such as strace, ftrace and truss allow a process to execute from start and report all system calls the process invokes, or can attach to an already running process and intercept any system call made by the said process if the operation does not violate the permissions of the user.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] This special ability of the program is usually also implemented with system calls such as ptrace or system calls on files in procfs.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] Implementing system calls requires a transfer of control from user space to kernel space, which involves some sort of architecture-specific feature.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] A typical way to implement this is to use a software interrupt or trap.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] Interrupts transfer control to the operating system kernel, so software simply needs to set up some register with the system call number needed, and execute the software interrupt.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] This is the only technique provided for many RISC processors, but CISC architectures such as x86 support additional techniques.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] For example, the x86 instruction set contains the instructions `SYSCALL`/`SYSRET` and `SYSENTER`/`SYSEXIT` (these two mechanisms were independently created by AMD and Intel, respectively, but in essence they do the same thing).
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] These are "fast" control transfer instructions that are designed to quickly transfer control to the kernel for a system call without the overhead of an interrupt.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] Linux 2.5 began using this on the x86, where available; formerly it used the `INT` instruction, where the system call number was placed in the `EAX` register before interrupt 0x80 was executed.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] An older mechanism is the call gate; originally used in Multics and later, for example, see call gate on the Intel x86.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] It allows a program to call a kernel function directly using a safe control transfer mechanism, which the operating system sets up in advance.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] For IA-64 architecture, `EPC` (Enter Privileged Code) instruction is used.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] The first eight system call arguments are passed in registers, and the rest are passed on the stack.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] In the IBM System/360 mainframe family, and its successors, a Supervisor Call instruction (SVC), with the number in the instruction rather than in a register, implements a system call for legacy facilities in most of IBM's own operating systems, and for all system calls in Linux.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] In later versions of MVS, IBM uses the Program Call (PC) instruction for many newer facilities.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] In particular, PC is used when the caller might be in Service Request Block (SRB) mode.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] The PDP-11 minicomputer used the EMT, TRAP and IOT instructions, which, similar to the IBM System/360 SVC and x86 INT, put the code in the instruction; they generate interrupts to specific addresses, transferring control to the operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] The VAX 32-bit successor to the PDP-11 series used the CHMK, CHME, and CHMS instructions to make system calls to privileged code at various levels; the code is an argument to the instruction.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] Within the RISC-V privileged architecture, the instruction `ECALL` (after *environment call*) is designed to enter a more privileged level and therefore this instruction performs the functionalities related to system calls.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] `ECALL` events are then handled in a similar fashion to other types of synchronous traps, including the same return mechanism.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] In the related Linux implementations, the system call number is placed into the `a7` (`x17`) register before `ECALL` is executed, function arguments are listed in accordance to the RISC-V ABI (`a0`, `a1`, ...) while the return value is put in `a0`.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] System calls in most Unix-like systems are processed in kernel mode, which is accomplished by changing the processor execution mode to a more privileged one, but no *process* context switch is necessary – although a *privilege* context switch does occur.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] The hardware sees the world in terms of the execution mode according to the processor status register, and processes are an abstraction provided by the operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] A system call does not generally require a context switch to another process; instead, it is processed in the context of whichever process invoked it.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] In a multithreaded process, system calls can be made from multiple threads.
[src:ebpf-security-monitoring/system-call] The handling of such calls is dependent on the design of the specific operating system kernel and the application runtime environment.
